{{Context|date=February 2009}}
'''Field Aligned Irregularities''' (FAIs) are [[anisotropic]] (different values when measured in different directions) perturbations of [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] density associated with [[magnetic field]]s. FAIs are often thought of in the context of the Earth's [[ionosphere]] where several natural processes generate FAIs in the [[E region|E-region]] and [[F region|F-region]]. They occur at 50 and 140 [[MHz]], where [[electrons]] associated with the event become vertically aligned with Earth's [[magnetic field]]. FAI may occur for several hours after it starts. Optimum times for observance appear to be between 8 PM and midnight.

