{{short description|A variety of porphyritic phonolite or trachyte with rhomb shaped phenocrysts of anorthoclase with variable olivine and augite in a glassy matrix}} [[File:Kenyte from Mount Kenya.jpg|thumb|right|Kenyte from Mount Kenya]] '''Kenyte''' is a variety of [[porphyritic]] [[phonolite]] or [[trachyte]] with rhomb shaped phenocrysts of [[anorthoclase]] with variable [[olivine]] and [[augite]] in a glassy [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. It was originally described and named by J. W. Gregory in 1900 for the occurrence on Mount Kenya.<ref>Roger Walter Le Maître, ''Igneous Rocks: A Classification and Glossary of Terms: Recommendations of the International Union of Geological Sciences Subcommission on the Systematics of Igneous Rocks,'' Cambridge University Press; 2nd ed., 2002, p. 96 {{ISBN|978-0-521-66215-4}}</ref><ref>J. W. Gregory, ''The Geological History of Mount Kenya,'' The Quarterly journal of the Geological Society of London, Volume 56, 1900, pp. 219-220</ref> Kenyte has also been reported from [[Mount Kilimanjaro]] and [[Mount Erebus]] in [[Antarctica]].<ref>Kyle, Philip R., ed., ''Volcanological and Environmental Studies of Mount Erebus, Antarctica,'' American Geophysical Union (December 1994), p. ''xi'' {{ISBN|978-0-87590-875-5}}</ref>
Kenyte has a glassy texture and may be composed of devitrified glass, which contains large [[phenocryst]]s of [[anorthoclase]] [[feldspar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mt. Kenya Volcano |url=http://www1.newark.ohio-state.edu/Professional/OSU/Faculty/jstjohn/Volcano%20stuff/Mt.-Kenya.htm |accessdate=13 July 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326120008/http://www1.newark.ohio-state.edu/Professional/OSU/Faculty/jstjohn/Volcano%20stuff/Mt.-Kenya.htm |archivedate=26 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>
